\par\par \b \uc2  Defending the rupiah. \b0\par\par\uc2 823 \uc2 words\par \uc2 6 July 2000\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  4 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2000 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  It seems that the government, notably \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (\b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 ), does not have a lot of ammunition to shore up the rate of the rupiah, which fell almost 4 percent over the last three days alone and is now hovering at a 16-month low of almost Rp 9,400 to the American dollar. \par \par \uc2  The government can do little because the main reason behind the sharp depreciation is not \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2 , financial or external but a sovereign risk associated with political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  One could easily see how the favorable key \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  indicators announced in May and June - lower than expected inflation, larger trade surplus and respectable \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth - were virtually unrelated to the rate of the rupiah. The currency began to tumble in early May after the International Monetary Fund postponed the disbursement of its second loan tranche because of the government's failure to meet its reform deadlines. \par \par \uc2  But the steep fall has since been fueled largely by a barrage of confusing and contradictory remarks from top policymakers, especially the erratic and controversial statements by President Abdurrahman Wahid himself which have sent shivers through the markets. \par \par \uc2  Abdurrahman's latest attack on his political opponents late last week further alarmed market participants who were already braced for rising political tension in the run-up to the General Session of the People's Consultative Assembly (MPR), the country's highest \b \highlight22\uc2 legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2  body. A bomb blast at the Attorney General's Office on Tuesday further roiled the market as the incident was seen as a signal of the kind of damage those being questioned as suspects or witnesses in corruption or political crime cases could do to the government or the nation. \par \par \uc2  Arriving on the heels of the legally questionable detention of \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  Governor Sjahril Sabirin, over the Bank Bali scandal last month, the President's instructions to Attorney General Marzuki Darusman to investigate several unnamed legislators raised bigger questions about political interference in the law. \par \par \uc2  This reminded many of former president Soeharto's style of government, through the rule of one man rather than the rule of law. And it concerned the market that the government is in disarray and not able to tackle its formidable political and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  challenges. \par \par \uc2  The \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  is really in a dilemma about how to manage the rate of the rupiah. \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  is prudent not to intervene in the market as such a measure, though strongly anticipated by the government, would waste the limited stock of precious foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  (only about US$16.2 billion) because the root cause of the fall is political. But simply doing nothing would smack of an abandonment of the currency. \par \par \uc2  The only effective weapon the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  can use to prevent a more rapid currency meltdown is its base-money \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  instrument. But even this instrument - interest rate \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  - can only be used sparingly in view of its devastating impact on the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  as a whole. \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  has already raised its benchmark interest rate over the past eight consecutive weeks to as high as 12.70 percent on Wednesday from 10.88 percent in early May. \par \par \uc2  But as market developments over the past two months have clearly demonstrated, the interest rate instrument has been less effective in curbing the rupiah's drop as it is the political risks, and not the yield factor, that counts right now. Raising this rate even further might lead to an unmanageable \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  as the interest burdens of the almost Rp 400 trillion ($45 billion) in treasury bonds, already issued to recapitalize state and private banks, would increase sharply. Higher \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  might also sabotage the nascent consumption-fueled recovery, plunging the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  into a worse crisis. \par \par \uc2  The best way to safeguard the currency is for the government to continue acting firmly to implement its reform agenda in order to sustain the budding recovery. A strong endorsement by the IMF, after its second review of the reform programs later this month, would contribute greatly to regaining market confidence in the long-term prospects of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . All this would further reduce Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and financial risks, two of the most important determinants of the rupiah rate. \par \par \uc2  But the most urgent factor needed right now to prevent another bout of wild volatility in the rupiah, is for government and political leaders, notably President Abdurrahman, to refrain from controversial and confusing remarks. \par \par \uc2  Political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  is never far from the surface in Indonesia, especially in the current transition to democracy, and in the run-up to the MPR session next month when the President will give an account of his first year in office. But daily market operations run on perception and not on \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  fundamentals that change merely on a monthly basis. Market perception can change from day to day because it is formed by information and statements by government and political leaders. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2000 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010812dw760052q\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
