\par\par \b \uc2  SATURDAY'S EDITORIALS IN INDONESIA'S MAJOR DAILIES. \b0\par\par\uc2 1,067 \uc2 words\par \uc2 8 July 2000\par \uc2 ANTARA - The Indonesian National News Agency\par \uc2 ANTARA\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2000 Asia Pulse Pte Limited. Asia Pulse gives no warranty or guarantee as to the accuracy of the information, Asia Pulse shall not be liable for errors or omissions in, or delays or interruptions to or cessation of delivery of, the data through its negligence or otherwise.\par \par \uc2  GROWTH PROSPECTS \par \par \uc2  Both private-sector and government analysts as well as international economists remain optimistic that Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would be capable of expanding by at least 4 percent this year despite the return of rupiah volatility and heated political tension in the run-up of the People's Consultative Assembly (MPR) session next month. \par \par \uc2  Analysts argue that most enterprises have adjusted themselves well to the rupiah zigzagging decline and to political woes. \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  concurs, saying there is no need to revise its macroeconomic targets, as the currency volatility and political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  are only temporary phenomenon. \par \par \uc2  The message of optimism, however, is not without pitfalls. A longer period of currency volatility would cast a shadow over the sustainability of the nascent recovery, as the consumer-led growth might peter out under a tight monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . A persistent zigzagging fall in the currency might also hinder the far-reaching corporate debt restructurization process that is so vital for the reinvigoration of the real sector. \par \par \uc2  Another potential snag to the recovery process is a cabinet reshuffle, which is strongly expected after the August MPR session. This move could make or break the credibility of the government. \par \par \uc2  On top of it all, the progress in the restructuring of the banking sector is perhaps the most determinant to a sustainable recovery. Because not a single \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  can sustain growth without a sound banking industry. The dilemma, though is that the banking industry cannot grow healthily in a depressed \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . - The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2  COURAGE \par \par \uc2  We would like to commend Attorney General Marzuki Darusman for his \par \par \uc2  courageous stand against the recent bombing of his office. Darusman said he did not feel at all intimidated and he and his staff are determined to finish all tasks at hand. \par \par \uc2  Destiny has played a significant role in his life. Several years ago he showed himself to be made of althogether different material when he decided to separate himself from the rest of the political pack. \par \par \uc2  Later after the forced resignation of Soeharto, he showed an uncompromising stance against former president Habibie, whom he rejected as presidential candidate of Golkar. Habibie later denounced him. \par \par \uc2  Marzuki's position as chairman of the National Committee for Human Rights gave him a splendid opportunity to deal with a difficult job, especially demonstrators who expected that all things could be resolved almost instantaneously. \par \par \uc2  Then followed his appointment as Attorney General. If somebody asks, not without a sneer, what is it that makes Marzuki Darusman so important in the present political set up, the answer may be short, but it is most convincing. He is honest. \par \par \uc2  If there are now those who would seek to dispose of him, it is all the more convincing that it is our national destiny to be condemned as a dishonest and dishonorable nation, due perhaps to our collective sins of the past. -The Indonesian Observer \par \par \uc2  MORAL MESSAGE FOR CIVILIAN LEADERS \par \par \uc2  Amidst the current climate of desperation, there emerged yesterday a joint \par \par \uc2  moral message issued by religious leaders. They view the national situation with mounting concern. According to the moral message, during the past two years, there has been no effort to promote unity among religious believers. The religious establishments have apparently issued their statements separately. \par \par \uc2  The most important part of the moral message is that the religious figures have asked the country's leaders to show empathy and concern upon the plight of the nation under crisis. \par \par \uc2  Difference in opinion among leaders is nothing naive. In every era, difference of opinion always exists. Civilian leaders Soekarno and Hatta once differed in opinion as regard the way to pursue democracy. Both refused to be emotional, let alone childish. Feeling being in a crossway with his colleague, Hatta opted to keep his own counsel and resigned from the post of vice president. For Hatta, bowing out for the good of the nation was wiser than flaring up with emotion to justify oneself. \par \par \uc2  Why do our present leaders - such as President Abdurrahman Wahid, Assembly Speaker Amien Rais, House Speaker Akbar Tandjung, and other politicians - refuse to take a lesson from out forefathers, Soekarno and Hatta? \par \par \uc2  If we continue to be like this (always fighting each other) and refuse to develop empathy and concern upon the plight of the nation, the present civilian government will not last long. Or, are the civilian leaders ready to concede power to the military? - Media Indonesia \par \par \uc2  MUHAMMADIYAH IN THE ERA OF REFORMS \par \par \uc2  Since 1980s, the Muhammadiyah (Islamic social) organization has been busy \par \par \uc2  dealing with the ideas of change and reforms, which are seen as issues of 'tajdid' (change for common good). Perhaps the ideas were then triggered by the publication of a study by Dr Mitsuo Nakamura, an anthropologist from Japan's Chiba University, who wrote his dissertation on the struggle of the Muhammadiyah to earn his doctorate from the Cornell University in the US. \par \par \uc2  How could Muhammadiyah rise under the suppression of the banyan tree (power-holder during the Soeharto regime), as alluded by Nakamura? Some carried out change by empowering the religious believers through \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development, but not a few young cadres entered \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  life through self-supporting movement of non-governmental organizations (NGOs) to arouse collective awareness upon the phenomenon of injustice and suppression facing them under the existing social and political system, either on national or global level. As a result, politics - which was avoided by most Muhammadiyah oldtimers - has been gradually entered by the organization's younger generation, who paved the political movement through university campuses and NGOs. This strategy does not abandon the conventional political struggle through political organizations and bureaucracy. \par \par \uc2  Like it or not, the Muhammadiyah has returned to the forum of political struggle. History has witnessed its young cadres to become motivators or even avant-garde of the reforms movement across the country. \par \par \uc2  If the Muhammadiyah has to take part in politics, it must have the nature of safeguarding the achievement of the target of high politics and undertake it in the management of comprehensive change as fought for by the Muhammadiyah young cadres. \par \par \uc2  The target of Muhammadiyah's high politics is "baldatun toyibatun warrobun ghofur" (prosperous country). In this connection, the potential of conflicts at the forum of practical politics among Islamic forces should be suppressed to a minimum in order to enable the realization of the objective of Islamic propagation in its widest sense. - Republika. \par \par \uc2 Document antara0020010804dw78004ti\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  BI probes overseas Rp transaction. \b0\par\par\uc2 666 \uc2 words\par \uc2 10 July 2000\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2000 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  is probing the sale of rupiah to buy US$ in the international market in order to ascertain the reason behind the weak currency, said BI senior official Made Sukada. \par \par \uc2  "The rupiah could be used to buy forex overseas. A transaction in New York forces the person who does so to seek rupiah. We are observing and evaluating this," he told the press here last week. \par \par \uc2  He also said that BI is also comparing it with transactions dome within the country. \par \par \uc2  If the purchase of dollars used rupiah from domestic banks, he added, it would be dealt with in a monetary manner "by, for example, absorbing liquidity." \par \par \uc2  If it comes from overseas, the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  would look into the matter, he said. \par \par \uc2  "If a person buys US$ over concern that the rupiah would fall, we would find out why the rupiah became weak. We would then find a remedy for it." \par \par \uc2  By ascertaining the sources of the purchase, Sukada went on to say the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  would take the necessary course of action. \par \par \uc2  "How could BI conduct moral-suasion if it does not know the sources of the purchase?" \par \par \uc2  Earlier, House member Theo F. Toemion said that moral-suasion with BI could help it cope with the problem of the weak rupiah. \par \par \uc2  Made added that the high fluctuation of a country's currency reflects its high risk. \par \par \uc2  The implication would be that banks would not be prepared to deal with forex in large amounts. \par \par \uc2  "They would surely reduce the volume in order to prevent speculation." \par \par \uc2  According to PT Danareksa Sekuritas economist Budi Hikmat