\par\par \b \uc2  Political conflict 'no longer scares foreign investors'. \b0\par\par\uc2 483 \uc2 words\par \uc2 19 July 2000\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  12 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2000 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Foreign investors in the manufacturing sector were more concerned about poor security and law enforcement than rivalries among the political elite, an analyst said. \par \par \uc2  "It (concern) is not about politics, but more about guarantee of security, law enforcement and consistency of investment regulations," Herman Latief, member of the advisory board of the Indonesian Industrial Estate Association (HKI), said on the sidelines of a seminar on prospect of investment in the industrial estate sector. \par \par \uc2  He said major foreign investors in the industrial estates had told the association they were not worried about the possibility of worsening political situation and had no plans to pull out of the country for that reason. \par \par \uc2  "That's because they've seen the worst during the 1997/1998 \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and political crisis. No matter what will happen in the political sector, it will not hurt us more," he said. \par \par \uc2  However, investors are very concerned about the rampant looting on their properties and conflicts over land ownership with locals, not to mention robbery of container trucks during delivery, he said. \par \par \uc2  Members of the association of electronics manufacturers recently complained about the rampant robberies of container trucks transporting electronics goods from factories to the harbors. \par \par \uc2  Investors in the forestry and pulp and paper industry have raised concerns with the government over land disputes with locals. \par \par \uc2  At the Batam Industrial Estate, management said investors in the area were particularly concerned about the government's inconsistency in the implementation of regulations, such as those regarding \b \highlight22\uc2 taxation\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Minister of Investment and State Enterprises Development Rozy Munir, who attended the seminar, acknowledged that his office had received many complaints from foreign investors about poor security, law enforcement and legal protection. \par \par \uc2  Rozy said one investor, being fed up with the country's lack of law enforcement and \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  regulations, decided to pull out, while another investor canceled investment plans over the same concerns. \par \par \uc2  Rozy, however, declined to name the companies. \par \par \uc2  Despite all the problems, Basroni Rizal, head of foreign affairs of HKI, said industrial estate operators started seeing positive growth in their business. \par \par \uc2  He said the operators were optimistic about the prospects for their business after seeing that most of the manufacturers had recovered from the impact of the crisis and started boosting output and hired more workers. \par \par \uc2  Herman, who is a commissioner of Lippo Cikarang Industrial Estate in Lemahabang, Bekasi, said sales of new industrial space had also improved. \par \par \uc2  "We saw sales increasing in the first quarter," he said, but did not provide details. \par \par \uc2  There are currently 65 industrial estates across the country accommodating more than 4,570 factories, about half of which are owned by foreign investors and manufacturers, especially Japanese and Korean, such as Sumitomo, Hyundai, Marubeni and Itochu. \par \par \uc2  Most of the estates, or 43 sites with about 2,100 factories, are located in Jakarta and West Java. (cst) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2000 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010812dw7j005sy\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
