\par\par \b \uc2  Gus Dur urged to make fundamental changes. \b0\par\par\uc2 756 \uc2 words\par \uc2 31 July 2000\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  2 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2000 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): House faction leaders have again denied they are planning to topple President Abdurrahman Wahid in the upcoming session of People's Consultative Assembly (MPR), but stressed that the President should make fundamental changes to the way he runs his government. \par \par \uc2  Heri Achmadi, secretary of the Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle (PDI-P) faction, said that despite mounting criticism directed against the government, the MPR's annual session from Aug. 7 until Aug. 18 would not be used to try the President but rather to evaluate the government's performance. \par \par \uc2  "All sides should realize the MPR general session is not a nightmare but an annual event as stipulated in the constitution to evaluate the government's progress," he said in a seminar on MPR general sessions and impeachment on Saturday. \par \par \uc2  He said the House had to remain critical of the President because of its constitutional roles to control the government and to function as a check-and-balance mechanism for the sake of the people's sovereignty. \par \par \uc2  "In fact, Gus Dur wants to pressurize the House if he himself is not under pressure," he said, referring to the President by his nickname. \par \par \uc2  Syamsul Mu'arif, chairman of the Golkar Party faction, agreed and said the way the President was running the government had prompted criticism from many groups, including the House and political parties. \par \par \uc2  He regretted that bearing in mind his physical limitations, Gus Dur was not wise enough to delegate his power to Vice President Megawati Soekarnoputri. \par \par \uc2  "So far, the President has yet to make good any policies to cope with political instability, the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis and the absence of the rule of law. Instead he has been busy handling unimportant matters," he said. \par \par \uc2  He said the Golkar faction fully supported the idea of delegating Gus Dur's power to Megawati to run the government, so that the President could concentrate on his main tasks as the head of state. \par \par \uc2  Hatta Radjasa, who chairs the Reform faction, deplored the overreaction of Gus Dur's supporters to rumors of an agenda to change the MPR general session into a special one. Hatta said the Assembly's annual session would be held to evaluate the President's performance and make necessary corrections to his progress report. \par \par \uc2  "It is good the MPR is convening annually but it's quite strange that the first annual session is coming into trouble when our president is Gus Dur. This means something wrong is happening with the government and, therefore, the Assembly should make an evaluation," he said. \par \par \uc2  He warned the President would lose his political legitimacy if he failed to change his leadership. \par \par \uc2  He said Gus Dur's fate was in the hands of the 700-member Assembly and would depend on the progress report he will present to the general session. \par \par \uc2  Suseno Yusuf, a member of the National Awakening Party (PKB) faction, said his party faction at the Assembly would be consistent in defending Abdurrahman's five-year term of office as stipulated by the constitution. \par \par \uc2  "All factions supporting Gus Dur in the last presidential elections should also follow suit because an annual replacement of the government would certainly trigger political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," he said. \par \par \uc2  He said that all parties, including PKB and the Nadhlatul Ulama, the country's largest Muslim organization, should remain critical of the President but should never support a move to impeach him. \par \par \uc2  Heri, Syamsul and Hatta agreed that violence and bloodshed would break out at the grassroots if Gus Dur was pressed to step down before his tenure ends. \par \par \uc2  J. Kristiadi, a political observer from the Center for Strategic and International Studies (CSIS) criticized the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the Assembly for \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  much time on political issues and giving less attention to the people's suffering. \par \par \uc2  "The people will swing to appreciate the much-criticized New Order government if the \b \highlight22\uc2 legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2  bodies fail to uphold their sovereignty. People do not care about political issues but they care about security guarantees and a better \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," he said. \par \par \uc2  He hailed the planned meeting between key political figures in Yogyakarta, saying it was important to create a conducive climate prior to the MPR general session. \par \par \uc2  "The informal meeting will be able to calm down the friction in the political elite and encourage the MPR to reach fruitful agreements in its session," he said. \par \par \uc2  He said all sides should realize the nation was learning democracy and it had to pay an expensive price for it. (rms) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2000 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010812dw7v00754\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw139\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2085\pichgoal600
