\par\par \b \uc2  President must be given chance to improve. \b0\par\par\uc2 756 \uc2 words\par \uc2 3 August 2000\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2000 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): While calling for a tighter rein on President Abdurrahman Wahid due to his glaring flaws which have come to the fore in the past 10 months, scholars warned that replacing him now would be politically more costly to the nation. \par \par \uc2  Respected Muslim scholar Nurcholish Madjid warned that there was no guarantee Abdurrahman's alternative would be any better or could bring about a better situation for the country. \par \par \uc2  Therefore, while finding the best way to correct a bad habit, it would be better to give the President a chance to improve his performance, Nurcholish said. \par \par \uc2  "In my view, the cost of accepting the current condition is still much, much more bearable than setting a precedent that we are not loyal to the Constitution," Nurcholish said in reference to suggestions of possibly removing the President. \par \par \uc2  "We may have to learn to live with Gus Dur," Nurcholish said during a discussion, held by The Jakarta Post at the Borobudur Hotel on Wednesday to mark the launching of the book Questioning Gus Dur. \par \par \uc2  The 249-page book of essays about the President from various prominent observers along with a few notable articles on Abdurrahman published in the newspaper, is an updated and revised edition of Understanding Gus Dur, which was launched earlier this year. \par \par \uc2  During Wednesday's discussion, Nurcholish did not widely elaborate on the best solutions to end Abdurrahman's leadership crisis. Nevertheless, he remarked on the empowerment of Vice President Megawati Soekarnoputri as one probable solution. \par \par \uc2  Nurcholish said Megawati deserved to play a key role in the government, because her party, the Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle (PDI Perjuangan), gained the highest vote in the general election. \par \par \uc2  "The Vice President must be more active because she also has strong legitimacy," he said. \par \par \uc2  Other guest speakers during Wednesday's discussion were political scientist Mochtar Pabotinggi of the National Institute of Sciences (LIPI) and noted economist Sjahrir. \par \par \uc2  Senior journalist and former Indonesian Ambassador to Australia Sabam Siagian moderated the seminar. \par \par \uc2  Budiman Soedjatmiko, the chairman of the Democratic People's Party (PRD), and labor activist Dita Indah Sari used the opportunity from the floor not only to slam the President, but also to warn of threats from the military and pro-status quo groups. \par \par \uc2  Budiman charged that political parties, including the Golkar Party and the "axis force", were trying to hold the President "hostage" so he bows to their political whims. \par \par \uc2  "Once he no longer abides by their orders, they will try to oust him," Budiman claimed. \par \par \uc2  Abdurrahman's second daughter, Yenny Zannuba Rahman, who was present during the discussion patiently listened to the sharp criticisms against her father. \par \par \uc2  Symbolic \par \par \uc2  Mochtar Pabotinggi maintained that while Abdurrahman may be incompetent he should remain as the head of state with his presidential powers reduced to a symbolic role. \par \par \uc2  Mochtar, however, disagreed with the suggestion to appoint either Megawati, the People's Consultative Assembly (MPR) Speaker Amien Rais or the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  Speaker Akbar Tandjung as the country's top executive. \par \par \uc2  He said these three individuals were no less incompetent than Abdurrahman. \par \par \uc2  "The most important thing is to end the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , because if this continues, pro-status quo and antireform groups will become the eventual winners in this chaos," he said. \par \par \uc2  Sjahrir, however, disputed Mochtar's proposal to limit the President's powers. \par \par \uc2  Sjahrir said it was unimaginable for a person like Abdurrahman to accept the reality that he would only play a ceremonial role. \par \par \uc2  "It is impossible for Gus Dur to accept such a bitter condition," he said. \par \par \uc2  Sjahrir said after the Assembly's Annual Session, which begins next week, the President should form a more credible and professional Cabinet. \par \par \uc2  He stressed that it was also important for Abdurrahman to stop his stubbornness and follow his \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  policymakers' advice. \par \par \uc2  "A market embracing government must be formed without ignoring the power of the existing political interests," Sjahrir noted. \par \par \uc2  In Sjahrir's opinion, not only was the President at fault over the past months but also legislators. \par \par \uc2  He said House members had been aggressive in probing the recent State Logistics Agency (Bulog) Rp 35 billion scandal which allegedly involved the President. \par \par \uc2  However, in comparison, the legislators seemed deaf when there were reports of alleged corruption for about Rp 190 billion disclosed by the recently removed Army Strategic \b \highlight22\uc2 Reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  Command (Kostrad) chief Lt. Gen. Agus Wirahadikusumah. \par \par \uc2  "Why did they just remain silent with the Kostrad case although the amount is so much higher than the Bulog case?" Sjahrir said. (prb) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2000 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010812dw83007ri\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
