\par\par \b \uc2  Reviewing debt deals. \b0\par\par\uc2 726 \uc2 words\par \uc2 3 August 2000\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  4 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2000 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  It is comforting to note that President Abdurrahman Wahid acted quickly to end the controversy caused by inconsistent and contradictory statements by senior \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  officials about the agreements hastily drawn with five conglomerates in October, 1998, for the settlement of billions of dollars of their debts to the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  The government reiterated its strong commitment to any legal contracts sanctioned by the present and previous governments, by announcing on Tuesday that the Masters of Settlement and Acquisition Agreement (MSAA) between the Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency (IBRA) and top business groups, for the settlement of about Rp 112 trillion (US$12.5 billion at the current exchange rate) in debts, would not be unilaterally scrapped. \par \par \uc2  The final decision, adopted at a Cabinet meeting on \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  affairs on Monday afternoon, removed the confusion set off by contradictory statements by Coordinating Minister for \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , Finance and Industry Kwik Kian Gie and IBRA chief Cacuk Sudarjanto late last month. Kwik initially stated that the debt settlement deals would simply be canceled, arguing that their enforcement would cause the state to lose at least Rp 80 trillion. He later moderated his stance, saying that the agreements would only be reviewed. Cacuk, however, staunchly defended the agreements, arguing that scrapping them would severely damage the credibility of IBRA in disposing the assets, worth about Rp 600 trillion, that it took over from closed and nationalized banks. \par \par \uc2  The government is really encountering a dilemma with regard to the MSAA, which was hastily concluded in October, 1998, to recoup the equivalent of billions of dollars in emergency loans extended by the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  to bail out banks formerly controlled by the conglomerates. Simply canceling the agreements would wipe out whatever little credibility the government still has amid the extreme lack of law enforcement, fragile security condition and political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Such unilateral action would also sabotage IBRA's present efforts to sell some of the assets to help plug the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 . But implementing them without any amendments would cause the government to lose billions of dollars due to the steep fall in asset value. \par \par \uc2  IBRA was under such tremendously strong political pressure in late 1998 to recoup the loans that it did not have enough time to thoroughly audit all of the hundreds of enterprises and independently appraise numerous other forms of assets pledged by the debtors to repay their debts. \par \par \uc2  One of the terms of the agreements that was then accepted as the best of an unfavorable set of options, but is now seen as legally flawed, was related to the clause that absolved the debtors of criminal wrongdoing in breaking banking rules. \par \par \uc2  Also seen now as quite damaging to the interests of the state is the other clause that discharged the debtors of any obligation to settle any balance that could arise later between what they had pledged and the amount of their debts. \par \par \uc2  These terms seemed to have been overlooked then as IBRA focused its attention on getting the top debtors to sign debt-settlement deals in an effort to recoup as much of the debts as possible. It was then regarded as less beneficial to the national interests to put the debtors in jail but leave their debts unrepaid. \par \par \uc2  Reviewing the deals would seem to be the best solution that would not affect the government's credibility in regard to honoring its commitments. But this review should involve independent auditors, appraisal companies and lawyers and be made as quickly as possible so as not to hold up IBRA's asset sales for any length of time. \par \par \uc2  The government obviously cannot do much in the way of legal claims if the sharp decline in the value of the assets has really been caused by the market condition. However, if the asset degradation was in the first place caused by the debtors themselves, then the agreements can be declared as legally flawed even by international standards. For that means that the debtors entered into the negotiations and the agreements in bad faith. \par \par \uc2  If the government claim is legitimate that many of the pledged assets were not covered by proper legal ownership titles or the assets turned out to be disputed by other parties, then the government has every legitimate reason to rework the deals and to file criminal proceedings against the debtors. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2000 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010812dw83007uc\par }\page {\par\fs20\b  \highlight22\uc2 Economy \highlight\uc2  Returns to  \highlight22\uc2 Uncertainty \highlight\uc2 . \b0\par\par\uc2 606 \uc2 words\par \uc2 4 August 2000\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2000 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  The Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  returns to \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  during the 3rd quarter of this year due to anxiety over the result of the national assembly \par \par \uc2  meeting. \par \par \uc2  Muhammad Ikhsan, an economist at LPEM management institute of the \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Faculty of the University of Indonesia says over the past several months the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  has been very much \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  because the positive perception of the market toward President Abdurrahman Wahid has turned to the opposite direction as is evident in rupiah depreciation and rising inflation. \par \par \uc2  There seems to be an erosion of trust in \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  toward the President's leadership and this is systematic in nature, he said during an Indef \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\par \par \uc2  and political research agency's workshop in Jakarta.The meeting was paritcipated in by People's Consultative Assembly Speaker Amien Rais, Chairman of PDI-P Faction at the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  Arifin Panigoro, and Chairman of National Awakening Party (PKB) Faction Taufikurrahman Saleh. Also addressing the workshop was Indef's noted economist Didik Rachbini and noted economist Bustanul Arifin. \par \par \uc2  Dr. Ikhsan said the negative market sentiment would only change if the MPR annual meeting produced satisfactory results. The MPR will meet on August 7-178. \par \par \uc2  Amien Rais and Arifin Panigoro stressed that the MPR meeting would not be directed at impeaching the President whatsoever. \par \par \uc2  Amien said MPR wouldonly listen to the President's progress report and then present some input to further improve the performance of the government. \par \par \uc2  Arifin Panigoro, meanwhile, said his faction would forward a proposal that is meant to push the government to work more effectively. Amien and Taufikurrahman agreed that the annual meeting of MPR would be utilized to discuss a concept that would put reform efforts on the right track. \par \par \uc2  Amien stressed that the President should after the August 7-18 meeting make his vision clear and get down to the details in order to become an effective national leader. "Otherwise there would be no more excuses," he said. \par \par \uc2  "I often draw this analogy," Amien said. "If Asian coutries hit by crisis are to be regarded as patients, then Malaysia, Korea, Thailand and the rest have all recovered, while Indonesia is still in the ICU, still being attended to by the doctor called IMF." \par \par \uc2  It is strange, he said, that everything the IMF requires of us has been done and we still have not recovered. \par \par \uc2  "Finance Minister Bambang Sudibio once told Gus Dur. It it goes on and on like this, the IMF would represent a neo-colonial power pretty much like the Dutch in the past and you, Gus Dur are Sultan Amangkurat II," Amien recalled. \par \par \uc2  Indef's economist Didik Rachbini said the President's leadership weakness was the cause for all the trouble and this also was the reason why recovery has been very slow. \par \par \uc2  He said the President should be able to act like a statesman. He lamented the fact that the government's performance resembled a rustic community being offered a modern supermarket, not knowing what to choose; whereas if one goes to the supermarket one must have the ability to choose the right thingsd to buy. And the buyer is confused, Didik said. \par \par \uc2  Amien Rais rejected the notion that the slow \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery has been caused by political bickering among the handful of national leaders. That's groundless, he said. \par \par \uc2  Foreign investors have not come and rupiah has been so volatile not because of the behavior of the political elite, Amien said. The political elite need to behave in that way because this is a democracy, and if nothing of that sort is done there the fear of authoritarianism would become so real, he argued. \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis0020010804dw84000j0\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
