\par\par \b \uc2  Councillor jailed for blackmailing palm oil company. \b0\par\par\uc2 807 \uc2 words\par \uc2 22 August 2000\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2000 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  BENGKULU (JP): A district court in Bengkulu sentenced on Saturday a local councillor and a "legal consultant" friend to seven years in jail for provoking locals to illegally demand land compensation from a foreign palm oil investor. \par \par \uc2  The panel of judges at the Argamakmur District Court in North Bengkulu regency found Mahidin Atu, deputy speaker of the local council, and "legal consultant" Zulkifli Ismail guilty of stirring up the villagers to destroy and burn PT Agro Muko's offices and buildings in North Mukomuko, costing the company Rp 900 million (about US$109,000). \par \par \uc2  Ismail claimed locally he was a legal consultant despite the fact he is a junior high school dropout. \par \par \uc2  The villagers demanded that Agro Muko pay Rp 16.05 billion in land compensation. \par \par \uc2  Agro Muko is a joint venture between Indonesian, British, German and Belgian companies. \par \par \uc2  Presiding judge Solahuddin said Mahiddin, as a \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  figure, was not supposed to use violence and blackmail in defending the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 's interest. \par \par \uc2  Zulkifli, as a legal consultant, was supposed to uphold the law rather than violate it, the judge further said. \par \par \uc2  Both defendants claimed their move was aimed at defending the rights of the local villagers but the judges found that both defendants had asked the villagers to share one-third of the compensation as a success fee. \par \par \uc2  "I regret the actions of both defendants, given the fact that the government is now taking pains to invite foreign investors to improve the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," Solahuddin said. \par \par \uc2  "The defendants' action has created a sense of legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  among foreign investors," he added. \par \par \uc2  Solahuddin stated Agro Muko's operations had brought a positive impact to the provincial \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , he said. \par \par \uc2  Mahidin, from the Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle (PDI Perjuangan), and his family members who were attending the court session, broke into tears after Solahuddin read out the panel of judges' decision. \par \par \uc2  Lawyer Hupoyo said he was satisfied with the court's decision despite the fact the jail term decided by the judges was two years lower than his demand. \par \par \uc2  He said the case could become be a good precedent for other similar cases elsewhere in the country. \par \par \uc2  "This is the first court decision in Bengkulu in favor of foreign investors," he said. \par \par \uc2  Agro Muko also welcomed the court's decision. \par \par \uc2  "We have to protect the rights of the foreign investors. Once they don't feel safe, they will run away," company advisor Murniyati said, adding the supremacy of law was the basic requirement for the country to attract investors. \par \par \uc2  Chairman of the Indonesia Palm Oil Producers Association Derom Bangun told The Jakarta Post on Monday that the court's decision was a good step for Indonesia to ensure investors about the country's legal certainty. \par \par \uc2  "It shows foreign investors that our country still has a willingness to enforce the law", Derom, who is also chairman of ASEAN Vegetable Oil Club, said. \par \par \uc2  Lawyer Ansjari Bachsin, representing Mahiddin and Zulkifli, told reporters after the court session he would appeal the decision. \par \par \uc2  He said Agro Muko had appropriated almost 4,000 hectares of land from the villagers but, thus far, had paid compensation to only a few of them. \par \par \uc2  He said the lives of the villagers were miserable because they had lost their land and had no jobs, given the fact that the company preferred to recruit outsiders to the locals. \par \par \uc2  Agro Muko started operating in Argamakmur in 1987 with a initial concession of 10,000 hectares. Since then, the company has expanded its palm oil plantation to 22,000 hectares. \par \par \uc2  The villagers of Teras Terunjam, Lubuk Sahung, Air Dikit, Pondok Linang and Saribulan claimed 4,000 hectares of the 10,000 hectares of land initially appropriated by the company belonged to their ancestors, and as such, had to pay them compensation. \par \par \uc2  However, the company said based on information from the local government, the land belonged to the state and the villagers were squatters. \par \par \uc2  The company was, thereby, only obliged by the local government to pay compensation for the plants grown by the villagers. \par \par \uc2  The company said it had paid compensation to the villagers for plants they had grown prior to the operations of the company but the villagers started protesting late last year to demand more compensation. \par \par \uc2  The protests culminated on Jan. 17, 2000 when about 500 villagers led by Mahiddin and Zulkifli went on the rampage, destroying and burning most of the property at the company's home base in North Mukomuko. \par \par \uc2  Many plantation and mining companies across the country have been facing troubles from local communities amid the breakdown of law and security following the resignation of former president Soeharto in 1998. \par \par \uc2  The villagers, who dared not speak out during Soeharto's administration, now claim investors wantonly took over their land without full compensation. (02) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2000 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010812dw8m0078p\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  Kadin chairman - Such market reactions are temporary. \b0\par\par\uc2 532 \uc2 words\par \uc2 24 August 2000\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 Eng