\par\par \b \uc2  FRIDAY'S EDITORIALS IN INDONESIA'S MAJOR DAILIES. \b0\par\par\uc2 1,230 \uc2 words\par \uc2 8 September 2000\par \uc2 ANTARA - The Indonesian National News Agency\par \uc2 ANTARA\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2000 Asia Pulse Pte Limited. Asia Pulse gives no warranty or guarantee as to the accuracy of the information, Asia Pulse shall not be liable for errors or omissions in, or delays or interruptions to or cessation of delivery of, the data through its negligence or otherwise.\par \par \uc2  A NATIONAL DISGRACE \par \par \uc2  Nearly one year since its separation from Indonesia, East Timor is still haunting the republic the way it always did when it was under Jakarta's occupation between 1975 and 1999. The brutal killing of at least three United Nations humanitarian workers by pro-Indonesian East Timorese in the West Timor border town of Atambua on Wednesday has brought nothing but shame and disgrace, not only to the government and the military, but also to the entire nation. \par \par \uc2  The repatriation of East Timorese refugees from Indonesia has now been halted indefinitely because the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) has abandoned all its offices in West Timor. An Indonesian government apology and a promise to improve the security of UN staffers will not likely convince the international community of Indonesia's sincerity. \par \par \uc2  A promise to investigate and punish the murderers will also be unconvincing given that Indonesia has not even begun trying those responsible for the mayhem in East Timor last year. The official investigation has only got as far as naming 19 suspects. Another promise, this time to prosecute the Atambua killers, would at best be welcomed with cynicism by the international community. \par \par \uc2  The least the Indonesian government should do to win back international confidence is to speed up the investigation into last year's atrocities. - The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2  OLD SOLDIERS \par \par \uc2  It is with sadness that we heard of the passing away on Wednesday of General \par \par \uc2  Abdul Haris Nasution, at Gatot Subroto military hospital. He was 81. \par \par \uc2  He left an illustrious career as one of the most accomplished generals in \par \par \uc2  the country's history. Not only did he prove his prowess as an excellent field commander when he defeated the communist rebels during the communist uprising in Madiun in 1948, he also served with success in administrative posts, such as minister of defense, and later on in the early states of the New Order regime when he served as Speaker of the People's Consultative Assembly (Provisional) (MPR-S). \par \par \uc2  Nasution also came to prominence in the West as a result of his conflict with former president Sukarno, which culminated in the political crisis known as the October 17, 1952 affair. \par \par \uc2  Since then, military and political observers in the West have often asked the question as to why Nasution, with his exceptional intelligence, never suceeded in becoming president of Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  Asked by a western journalist why he never made the grade, Nasution said that he never felt sure that the people of Java would ever accept a candidate from the province outside Java. From then on he was called the Hamlet of Indonesian politics, after the famous figure from the play by William Shakespeare. But for us, his memory will live on as one of the greatest sons of Indonesia, and a man who has served honorably the country which he has always loved. \par \par \uc2  Rest in Peace, General Nasution. - The Indonesian Observer \par \par \uc2  WE ARE NOT A KILLER NATION \par \par \uc2  We have yet to carry out the trial of people allegedly involved in human rights violations in East Timor. Yet, we now face another very difficult problem - three staff members of the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees were killed in the small town of Atambua in East Nusa Tenggara near the border with East Timor. \par \par \uc2  President Abdurrahman Wahid, who is in New York, has faced many criticisms over the incident, including from UN Secretary General Kofi Annan and US President Bill Clinton and it was not easy for him to answer their questions. \par \par \uc2  We deplore the bloody incident.  We however want the world to be \par \par \uc2  responsible. \par \par \uc2  The present situation in East Timor is something Indonesia never wanted to \par \par \uc2  see.  Portugal, which had abandoned its former colony, has never shown its full \par \par \uc2  responsibility. \par \par \uc2  Xanana Gusmao, Ramos Horta, and other East Timorese independence figures \par \par \uc2  have the tendency to wash their hands after they have begun to enjoy popularity. \par \par \uc2  They have no real initiative and concrete steps to restore law and order in \par \par \uc2  their country. \par \par \uc2  There is no real commitment as well from countries which have fully \par \par \uc2  supported East Timor's independence to help rebuild the territory. \par \par \uc2  We thus reject all criticisms that corner Indonesia.  We are not a killer \par \par \uc2  nation. - Media Indonesia \par \par \uc2  OPTIMISM NEEDED, SO IS AN UNDERSTANDING OF REALITY \par \par \uc2  Once again, we have to express our great appreciation to the new cabinet for the optimism they bring and for the hopes they are trying to build. From various statements they have made, we could feel the ministers' optimism amid their will to lead this nation out of its \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  hardship. \par \par \uc2  Thus, President Abdurrahman Wahid's intention to buy a presidential aircraft - ala Air Force One - has come as a surprise to us. It is an example of a practice where an intention to rebuild hopes and the nation's identity appear without the intention to see the reality faced by the nation. \par \par \uc2  The reason behind the president's wish sounds reasonable - that the purchase of an airplane is aimed at supporting presidential activities. Moreover, it was supported by a preamble that the current use of Garuda Indonesia aircraft might disturb the airline's commercial activities. \par \par \uc2  Despite these reasons however, the wish to purchase a special presidential aircraft is an absurdity. Imagine, amid \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  concerns over the impending fuel price hike, the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  of whether or not the target revenues of the 2000 state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  would be met, problems on how to cover the Rp 53 trillion \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  of the 2001 state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 , about 100 million Indonesians living in poverty, about 36 million people unemployed, there is a wish - which is absolutely not urgent - to own a special presidential aircraft. \par \par \uc2  We hope that the recent statement made by the president denying that he intends to purchase a presidential aircraft is true. We can thus leave the unnecessary controversies behind and just go back to our main duties of restoring the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , upholding the law, maintaining security, and giving justice and prosperity to the entire nation. - Kompas \par \par \uc2  A DELUGE OF CARS AND ITS IMPACT \par \par \uc2  A traffic jam was created around the Jakarta Convention Center (JCC) last \par \par \uc2  Wednesday due to the opening of the 10th "Gaikindo Auto Show". \par \par \uc2  It was reportedly the largest car exhibition ever held, participated in by \par \par \uc2  108 companies, including 23 sole agents.  It will last until Sept 12. \par \par \uc2  The cars exhibited include luxury cars and those completely built-up (CBU). \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Public\b0 \highlight\uc2  interest for the auto show caused the traffic jam. \par \par \uc2  Data obtained from Gaikindo (the Indonesian Association of Car \par \par \uc2  Manufacturers) showed that total car sales in the first half of the year have reached 126,944 units, marking a 555 percent increase compared to the same period last year. \par \par \uc2  At least 2,400,000 vehicles have been registered in Jakarta, and the increase in the number of vehicles has never matched the length of roads in this capital city. This has made Jakarta the third most polluted city in the world, after Mexico City and Bangkok. \par \par \uc2  On one hand, the strengthening of the automotive business was impressive. \par \par \uc2  On the other hand though, it brings about a bad impact to the environment. \par \par \uc2  Pollution and traffic jams, the results of an imbalance between the number \par \par \uc2  of vehicles and the length of roads, have caused a reduction in work productivity. There is thus an urgent need for more \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  transportation. - Bisnis Indonesia. \par \par \uc2 Document antara0020010804dw98000px\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw139\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2085\pichgoal600
