\par\par \b \uc2  The future of toll road investment. \b0\par\par\uc2 702 \uc2 words\par \uc2 21 September 2000\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  4 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2000 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  This is the first of two articles on Indonesia's toll road sector by Heru Dewanto, the executive director of the Jakarta-based Center for Technology and Industry Development. \par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): The Asian \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis has cast a long, though uneven shadow over the region. It also has led to a severe decline in infrastructure investment in Indonesia. Major investments in electric power, transportation and telecommunications infrastructure, much of which was supported by the private sector, have had to be deferred, and investment in Indonesian toll roads is no exception. \par \par \uc2  It was in 1978 that the first toll road in Indonesia was opened for operation, and the state-owned toll road corporation, Jasa Marga, was established as both the state toll road authority and operator. \par \par \uc2  The government made its \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  clear at that time: toll roads, built to the highest standards, are legal only as alternative routes to existing roads, thus enabling motorists to take the toll-free option. This is in line with global practice. \par \par \uc2  Since the first toll road opened, Indonesia now has 515 kilometers of toll roads, consisting of 354 kilometers owned by Jasa Marga and 161 kilometers operated by the private sector under Build-Operate-Transfer (BOT) schemes. \par \par \uc2  The government allowed Jasa Marga to develop into a strong national corporation, with initially strong government support. Between 1995 and 1996, Indonesia succeeded in attracting the interest of international competitors in BOT concessions for 19 toll road projects, with a total length of 767 kilometers and an investment estimated at US$3.5 billion. \par \par \uc2  These projects had the potential to stimulate the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  just prior to the onset of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis. \par \par \uc2  Because of the rapidly developing \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , with traffic growth rates of between 7 percent and 15 percent per annum around the main wealth-generating urban areas, the high cost of capital here, in addition to short-term \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  in assessing traffic flows and tariffs, were able to be accommodated. \par \par \uc2  On the other hand, when the network was extended to smaller urban areas and long intercity links in slower growing \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  areas, traffic build-up \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  and limits on Jasa Marga's ability to provide support became constraints on further expansion in the face of higher financing costs. \par \par \uc2  In fact, behind the success story of private toll road development a number of fundamental questions remained unanswered. \par \par \uc2  The decision to introduce the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  on toll road development was driven by the recognized limitations of government funding to meet increasing demands for transportation, and to overcome intolerable traffic congestion in a rapidly developing \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Congestion causes inefficiency and significant increases in travel costs. \par \par \uc2  In developing areas, the external costs are internalized in the form of toll charges. The toll charges can then be allocated to build or increase the capacity of toll roads, as well as providing for their maintenance. \par \par \uc2  The user-pay system must therefore offset the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  costs of under-use of a toll road in the early years, if this is the case, and the need to maintain the existing or parallel \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  roads. \par \par \uc2  In this way, the government can focus their \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  on constructing roads in less developed areas, without neglecting or spoiling the self-perpetuating nature of growth in the areas that have begun to take off. \par \par \uc2  While the first generation of toll roads was fully financed by the national \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the second generation required financing from foreign soft loans. \par \par \uc2  As the rate of development could no longer be supported by the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  alone, the government had to invite private sector participation in order to keep the \b \highlight22\uc2 national debt\b0 \highlight\uc2 -to-equity ratio at a manageable level. \par \par \uc2  Private-owned toll roads have been developed on the basis of the BOT scheme in a form of cooperation with Jasa Marga. The first generation of private toll road companies had the advantage of not having to cover the land acquisition costs. \par \par \uc2  This no longer holds, however, and the private sector not only has to bear this \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2 , but also must take all the risks associated with land clearing. This can be a problem, particularly for projects that are only marginally viable in terms of return on investment. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2000 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010812dw9l003bj\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
