\par\par \b \uc2  The future of toll road investment. \b0\par\par\uc2 1,386 \uc2 words\par \uc2 22 September 2000\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  4 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2000 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  The following is the second of two articles on the toll road sector by Heru Dewanto, executive director of the Jakarta-based Center for Technology and Industry Development. \par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Before the crisis, the toll road sector had made reasonable progress, with improvements taking place in procedures and frameworks for wider private sector participation. A large program of investment was moving along, and the sector was approaching some maturity, in which fine-tuning of processes, improving efficiency and the scale of operations were becoming the main concerns. \par \par \uc2  The remaining key issues concerned the land procurement process and pricing, the mechanism for adjusting toll rates, the method of increasing the scale of operations without over-stretching the participation and creditworthiness enhancements provided by Jasa Marga, the National Toll Road Corporation, and the transition to a transparent, evenhanded competition. \par \par \uc2  The crisis has affected existing private-owned toll roads and paralyzed many projects that had been approaching financial closure or which were already under construction. \par \par \uc2  In 1996, a number of projects were awarded to a range of local and international bidders for 19 different sections of toll roads. However, actual development came under the severest pressure, and virtually all of the winning bidders have ended up in serious, if not impossible, difficulties that affected implementation under the agreed terms and conditions, because of the impact of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis. \par \par \uc2  Their financial basis is in serious question and in most cases the projects were eventually considered untenable. \par \par \uc2  The slump in the overall \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth has in a way presented a window of opportunity in which to reassess and re-evaluate future strategies for this important sector. A better future for toll road investment in Indonesia needs to be carefully planned, and this must be done now. \par \par \uc2  Of particular urgency is the need to review the extent and the size of the various project risks to be borne by the government and the project sponsors. It is also important to create a situation in which the various parties involved are able to address these risks in the changed situation. \par \par \uc2  In late 1997, in response to the crisis, the government drew up a list of infrastructure projects, these being classified as to continue, to be postponed, or canceled. \par \par \uc2  The classification, however, seems to have been based more on project readiness, i.e. its stage of development, whether physical or financial, rather than on the potential of the project to assist in reviving regional development or the recovery of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  as a whole. \par \par \uc2  Since then, the whole political scene has been changing as a result of the institution of major reforms; a new paradigm has been emerging that will affect the manner of future development. \par \par \uc2  A key element of this is the restructuring of the banking sector and, parallel to this, the efforts of large private sector corporations, many with interests in infrastructure, to restructure crippling debts. The revival of the real sector hinges on this. \par \par \uc2  However, an apparent consequence of the focus on these fundamental issues is a general insufficient attention paid to the importance of primary infrastructure development as part of the strategy for \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery. \par \par \uc2  It is important that this issue attracts political and government support at an early date. The question is how to pick up the previously stimulating progress, which has been obstructed by the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis. \par \par \uc2  Local traffic, as a result of there being no adequate toll road alternatives, has become chaotic for much of any day. While the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  quietly questioned project investment awards in the past, and to some degree some of these awards might be seen as having contributed to the crisis, the lack of development in this sector now will even slow down the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery. \par \par \uc2  Private toll road companies have been seeking ways out of their problems. Some have made individual approaches by inviting new foreign strategic investors to assume their debt in return for substantial shareholding in the toll road companies. \par \par \uc2  This or a rescheduling of debt seems to be the only possible action to take, but there has been no success to date, because of the perceived \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery. \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, the Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency (IBRA) has taken over almost all private toll road companies and placed them under their asset management unit. \par \par \uc2  IBRA's main remit, however, is to restructure those companies' debts at Indonesian banks. This is not sufficiently comprehensive, unfortunately, and the lack of a nationwide strategy that includes infrastructure development as one of the key elements in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery is still of concern. \par \par \uc2  In the medium-term, the postponement of projects in the pipeline will have a negative impact on the infrastructure sector; the overall availability of infrastructure services; and the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in general. Further delay will prove to be costly. \par \par \uc2  In the longer term, on the positive side there is an opportunity to learn from this crisis, especially for improving the fundamental structure of the institutional framework of toll road development and for private sector investment in toll road projects. \par \par \uc2  The real challenge now is how to mobilize community and political support. There is a need to review the role of infrastructure, including toll roads, in supporting \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery, through a study on how the regional \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is enhanced as a result of infrastructure development. \par \par \uc2  There is available precrisis evidence which can be used as a basis for this work. A systematic parallel effort in \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  relations is also required to inform the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  and obtain their support behind beneficial and socially sustainable projects. \par \par \uc2  In this window of opportunity for reformulating the current approach, all institutional and political parties and the communities affected will need to feel confident in the process, and be assured of the reliability of the long-term legal process. \par \par \uc2  It is time to rethink the relative roles of government, Jasa Marga, investors, financiers, the various structures and instruments of development, and to reassign net risk responsibility. \par \par \uc2  The coming devolution of autonomy to the regions will also endorse new approaches from domestic and regional as well as global investors in the sector. \par \par \uc2  One immediate outcome of the financial structuring of toll road projects will be the need for a strong domestic capital market. Inputs of foreign funds should be used only as a supplement to domestic funding, rather than being the main source of funding. However, the depth of the crisis is such that short-term reliance on foreign loans cannot be avoided. \par \par \uc2  There also needs to be an improved balance in risk allocation between the government and the private sector in order to avoid high private financing cost or heavy leveraging due to widespread use of government guarantees. \par \par \uc2  Institutional framework reforms should include taking away the client role from Jasa Marga and returning it to the government. Its role should be exclusively as an operator and investor in toll roads. \par \par \uc2  Cooperation between the state-owned toll road company, provincial government-owned bodies and private sector concerns must be based purely on profitability. \par \par \uc2  The next task is to establish a competitive market. This will need setting enabling conditions across many diverse areas such as legal and regulatory regimes, \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  reforms and designing incentives for technological upgrades. \par \par \uc2  In parallel, in a wider context, the holding structure of national toll companies should be altered. Finally, a new holding umbrella for each metropolitan area may be needed to cover all toll road companies within those areas, with another one established for regional toll road companies. \par \par \uc2  Toll road development in Indonesia has an unquestionably auspicious prospect. The government has prepared a very ambitious program, based on a reasonable forecast of demand. \par \par \uc2  In the short-term, a number of toll road projects that have been postponed or slowed down are being reviewed with a view to recommence as the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovers. \par \par \uc2  The previously planned program is still considered valid in the long run. In fact, the demand is there and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth is expected to reach the previous level as the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  gradually recuperates. \par \par \uc2  The crisis has caused a temporary halt, and yet in view of the long-term potential of toll road development in this country, this could be seen positively as a moment of truth: to reflect and acknowledge any shortcomings, muster all the energy and then move on afresh. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2000 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010812dw9m003fd\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw139\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2085\pichgoal600
