\par\par \b \uc2  Atambua issue may hurt RI efforts at CGI meeting. \b0\par\par\uc2  By Berni K. Moestafa \par \uc2 706 \uc2 words\par \uc2 14 October 2000\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2000 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): The World Bank (WB) warned on Friday that improper handling of militias in Atambuwa, East Nusa Tenggara or West Timor, might hurt Indonesia's efforts to obtain US$4.8 billion in soft loans at next week's meeting of the Consultative Group on Indonesia (CGI) in Tokyo. \par \par \uc2  "In the lead up to the Tokyo meeting, a number of donors and members of civil society have raised concerns about recent developments in West Timor," visiting WB vice president for East Asia and the Pacific Jemal-ud-din Kassum said in a press meeting. \par \par \uc2  Kassum fell short of saying whether donor countries might actually cut financial aid to Indonesia if the handling of the militias did not meet the donors' expectation. \par \par \uc2  He said that Coordinating Minister for Political Security and Social Affairs Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono had meet representatives of donor countries in response to their concerns. \par \par \uc2  The minister, he said, briefed the representatives on the current actions taken by the government. "Continued progress on this issue will provide a positive environment for donor support," he added. \par \par \uc2  The CGI meeting will be held between Oct. 17 and 18 in Tokyo, where Indonesia is expecting to receive US$4.8 billion in soft loans to help lower its gaping \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  However, last month's Atambua incident in West Timor, where East Timor militias killed three United Nations workers, has dent the prospect of continued international support. \par \par \uc2  The United Nations issued Resolution No. 1319/2000, ordering Indonesia to disarm and disband the militias while also restoring law and order in the region. \par \par \uc2  William Cohen, The United States' Defense Secretary warned of international isolation that further damaged foreign investors' confidence in the country. \par \par \uc2  Kassum, who will chair next week's CGI meeting, cautioned against eroding market confidence but he said that Indonesia continued to show signs of recovery. \par \par \uc2  "Despite jittery markets, nervous investors and fragile consumer confidence, Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  continues to show signs of recovery," he said. \par \par \uc2  However, he said that financial markets remained unconvinced by the developments in the real \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 , regional unrest and periodic outbursts of violence combined with \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  slippage on the structural reform agenda could still derail \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery, he continued. \par \par \uc2  Speaking to the press at the launching of the World Bank's Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  outlook report, Kassum said that in the short term, restoring confidence was key to accelerating the recovery. \par \par \uc2  The World Bank released on Friday its Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  outlook report to be discussed at the CGI meeting. \par \par \uc2  According to the report, Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth had expanded to beyond a consumption driven base growth, with investments starting to contribute. \par \par \uc2  It said that inflation was under control, real wages were rising again, and that poverty had declined from a punishing peak of over 23 percent. \par \par \uc2  The World Bank emphasized the need for visible results in three key areas: bank and corporate restructuring, a carefully implemented decentralization, and \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  consolidation. \par \par \uc2  "In the medium term, we consider poverty reduction and good governance - which are closely interrelated - as the central challenges for Indonesia," Kassum said. \par \par \uc2  The report said that misdirected \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  shortchanged poverty programs, monopolies threatened small businesses and illegal fees and levies prevented the poor from accessing government services. \par \par \uc2  "Weak governance hit the poor the hardest," Kassum added. \par \par \uc2  Separately, \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  issued its quarterly report on the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which predicted difficult times ahead. \par \par \uc2  "Generally the challenges ahead are getting tougher along with rising pressure on inflation and the weakening of the rupiah," BI's report said. \par \par \uc2  The \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  estimated inflation to rise one percent above the initial target of between five percent to seven percent. \par \par \uc2  Although the current inflation rate was still 4.65 percent below BI's target, a recent decision to hike fuel prices will likely push the consumer price index up. \par \par \uc2  The report said that consumption growth, which had been pushing the recovery so far, had also slowed down. \par \par \uc2  However, investment activities showed signs of recovery as seen on climbing imports and a rise in banking credits channeled. \par \par \uc2  During the second quarter, investment constituted the second largest contributor to the gross domestic production (GDP), after exports, the report said. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2000 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010812dwae0010w\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
