\par\par \b \uc2  Shake-up at IBRA. \b0\par\par\uc2 707 \uc2 words\par \uc2 17 October 2000\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  4 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2000 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Firing the second-highest executive of the agency that holds the key to Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery while he was overseas leading a road show to attract investors was the last thing President Abdurrahman Wahid needed to do to improve the credibility of his \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis-management system. The President's abrupt decision last week to replace Arwin Rasyid as vice chairman of the Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency will only strengthen the market's perception that his management system is erratic, at best. \par \par \uc2  The timing and unclear reasons for the dismissal of Arwin after only about 10 months in his position, and strong rumors of the imminent replacement of Cacuk Sudarijanto as IBRA chairman, though weakly denied by the President's spokesman Wimar Witoelar on Monday, will only cause more damage to the working spirit at the agency. \par \par \uc2  We thought the political struggle for control of IBRA, which holds more than Rp 600 trillion (US$68.2 billion) in state assets, or as much as 40 percent of gross domestic product, ended when Abdurrahman moved last November to make the agency answerable only to him. But the top management at IBRA seems to remain highly vulnerable to squabbles within the political elite. \par \par \uc2  Bambang Subianto, the first chairman of the agency that was set up by then president Soeharto in late January 1998, served for only about two months. Bambang Subianto's successor, Iwan R. Prawiranata, survived for approximately three months. The third chairman, Glenn M. Yusuf, served the longest tenure, weathering a turbulent 18 months. Cacuk, whose status is now highly \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2 , was appointed only last December. \par \par \uc2  Such instability and discontinuity in the top management is devastating to the capability of the agency to carry out its vital role of helping to lead the nation out of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis. \par \par \uc2  IBRA's tasks of salvaging the banking industry, resolving the huge corporate debt overhang and restructuring the paralyzed business sector requires not only strong leadership, but also some sort of continuity in management. Debt restructuring is a complex, time-consuming process. \par \par \uc2  How can IBRA management develop strong leadership if its key executives can be replaced anytime, without clear reason? If this tendency continues, key officials, who by the nature of their jobs will always face temptations from big debtors to "collude or corrupt", could opt for the easy way out, acting in very short-term interests at the expense of the national \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  True, IBRA's performance is still way below expectations. Its bank and debt restructuring programs have always been far behind schedule and its asset recovery has always been far short of the targets. Its latest debt restructuring deals, involving more than $3.7 billion owed by four conglomerates, exploded into a controversy that spooked the international market and multilateral agencies, and could become a hot potato for Indonesia's delegation at the meeting of the Consultative Group on Indonesia creditor consortium in Tokyo beginning on Tuesday. \par \par \uc2  It is, however, not fair to pin all of the blame for this subpar performance on IBRA management. In addition to the instability of its management in the first seven months of its operations, the agency has been held hostage to political battles between various influential groups. \par \par \uc2  Abdurrahman's move to put IBRA directly under his control was initially hailed as the right step to protect the agency from vested political interests and to gradually develop it into an independent institution, able to perform freely its functions. But the President's latest tinkering with its top management once again proves how chaotic has been Abdurrahman's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2 -management system. \par \par \uc2  Letting IBRA drift much longer will derail the nascent \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery. It is therefore imperative that the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  ask for the government's accountability regarding the agency. We are also utterly disappointed with the Oversight Committee of IBRA, which seems to serve only as a perfunctory body. The committee, consisting of independent experts under the leadership of Mar'ie Muhammad, a former finance minister who was known as "Mr. Clean" during the corrupt Soeharto regime, should be more assertive in exercising its authority, acting quickly and firmly to enforce the long-delayed good governance system at the agency. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2000 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010812dwah000wi\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  ADB -  \highlight22\uc2 Budget deficit \highlight\uc2  and debts halt recovery. \b0\par\par\uc2 268 \uc2 words\par \uc2 19 October 2000\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2000 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  MANILA (AFP): The Asian Development Bank has warned \par \par \uc2  that \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  and foreign debts of Indonesia, \par \par \uc2  the Philippines and Thailand may halt the countries' \par \par \uc2  recovery efforts. \par \par \uc2  The governments oif these countries must pay serious \par \par \uc2  attention to the problems, the agency said. \par \par \uc2  If the \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  position worsens, investment and \par \par \uc2  recovery would be jeopardized. In this situation, \par \par \uc2  there would be heavier pressure on bank \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\par \par \uc2  due to \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  loan increase and investments would be \par \par \uc2  in jeopardy, it said in an annual report, called Asia \par \par \uc2  Recovery Report, released Wednesday. \par \par \uc2  It said up to the end of September Indonesian rupiah \par \par \uc2  had depreciated by 19%, Philipine peso by 13% and Thai \par \par \uc2  baht 11%. \par \par \uc2  It said Indonesia needs more than two more years to \par \par \uc2  regain the level of growth it had before the crisis \par \par \uc2  erupted but Thailand would need a shorter period of \par \par \uc2  time for the same purpose. \par \par \uc2  It also noted that polical \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  was to blame \par \par \uc2  for slow \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery. \par \par \uc2  Pradumna Rana, an ADB official, said the main factor \par \par \uc2  causing the worsening of \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  position of Indonesia \par \par \uc2  was the huge funds it allocated for corporate \par \par \uc2  restructuring. \par \par \uc2  The government has bitten off more than it can chew, \par \par \uc2  the official said, adding that he had some worries \par \par \uc2  about continued rupiah depreciation and rising trend \par \par \uc2  of bank \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  ADB expects Indonesia to grow at 4% this year, while \par \par \uc2  Thailand will have a growth rate of 5%-6% and South \par \par \uc2  Korea and Malaysia will grow at over 8%. It added \par \par \uc2  that South Korea had implemented the right therapy for \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery but the other countries had not. (ram). \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis0020010804dwaj000nv\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw139\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2085\pichgoal600
