\par\par \b \uc2  Gus Dur comes under fire. \b0\par\par\uc2 905 \uc2 words\par \uc2 21 October 2000\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2000 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): President Abdurrahman Wahid's instruction to delay the prosecution of three of the country's top indebted businessmen could damage the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the legal system, analysts here said on Friday. \par \par \uc2  Lin Che Wei, an analyst at a foreign securities firm, said the move would create legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  because people would think that the President could intervene in legal proceedings and that a legal process could be influenced by a "business deal." \par \par \uc2  "Instead of helping the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , I think this is very damaging to the business environment," Che Wei said. \par \par \uc2  Abdurrahman, popularly known as Gus Dur, disclosed his controversial decision in Seoul during a gathering with the Indonesian community in South Korea. \par \par \uc2  Gus Dur admitted that he had ordered the Attorney General's Office to delay the prosecution of Texmaco Group chairman Marimutu Sinivasan, Barito Pacific Group chairman Prajogo Pangestu, and the chairman of the Gadjah Tunggal Group, Syamsul Nursalim. \par \par \uc2  "This (move) is necessary because the business groups are major exporters who can contribute greatly to the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery process," the President said. \par \par \uc2  The three businessmen owe billions of dollars in bad debts to the Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency (IBRA), a unit of the finance ministry. \par \par \uc2  Che Wei said that if the government wanted to boost exports it should focus on industries with high competitive advantages. \par \par \uc2  "Textiles is one example, but certainly not petrochemicals or the shrimp farming business," he said. \par \par \uc2  Prajogo is the co-owner of PT Chandra Asri, a petrochemical center in West Java, whose debt restructuring process has been criticized as a government bailout. \par \par \uc2  Syamsul is the owner of an integrated shrimp industry company PT Dipasena, which had been pledged to IBRA to repay debts to the government, but its assets have been deteriorating sharply due to disputes with local shrimp farmers. \par \par \uc2  "The problem is that the spirit (of the President's decision) is not to save the industry but to save the businessmen," Che Wei pointed out. \par \par \uc2  He stressed that legal certainty was crucial to revive investor confidence in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Separately, Center for Strategic and International Studies (CSIS) economist Hadi Soesastro said that the controversial decision would create a bad precedent. \par \par \uc2  "Other indebted conglomerates would also demand similar treatment," Hadi said. \par \par \uc2  IBRA has received $31 billion in bad loans from the country's banking sector. About $26 billion of the total is owed by only around 20 of the largest debtors, including the three business groups. \par \par \uc2  The agency has often warned it will take strong legal action against debtors who are not willing to negotiate debt restructuring in good faith. \par \par \uc2  IBRA is also trying to force former bank owners, including Syamsul (former owner of the now defunct Bank BDNI), to add more assets to repay their banks' debt to the government. Coordinating Minister for \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Affairs Rizal Ramli has said that legal action would also be taken against uncooperative ex-bank owners. \par \par \uc2  "It is very important that the government provides the same treatment in dealing with IBRA debtors," Hadi said. \par \par \uc2  Amien Rais, Speaker of the People Consultative Assembly (MPR), deplored the President's remarks, citing them as a bad legal precedence. \par \par \uc2  "The three conglomerates' sins are unforgivable. There should be no apology for those who embezzled hundreds of trillions of rupiah belonging to the people," Amien retorted. \par \par \uc2  He said the reasons given for the President's decision were groundless. \par \par \uc2  "Seen from a legal aspect, the three businessmen's status is actually not much different from that of Mohhamad Bob Hasan," Amien added. \par \par \uc2  Separately, \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  Speaker Akbar Tandjung said he did not see any reasonable connection between the three tycoons' case with their supposed major contribution to \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development. \par \par \uc2  "The three tycoons should be prosecuted if they are guilty. The primacy of the law must be upheld and all should be treated equal in the face of the law," he said after attending a ceremony to celebrate the Golkar Party's anniversary here on Friday. \par \par \uc2  He said Golkar did not support the President's stance. \par \par \uc2  The government recently came under strong criticism from the International Monetary Fund and World Bank for what they called questionable debt workout deals with four conglomerates. \par \par \uc2  In May, the Attorney General's Office stopped investigations into corruption allegations against Sinivasan, saying that there was simply no evidence of wrongdoing related to Texmaco's loans from state banks. \par \par \uc2  Revrisond Baswir of Gadjah Mada University saw Abdurrahman's move as an attempt to nurture a special group of conglomerates as his cashcow, just as his predecessors Soekarno and Soeharto had done. \par \par \uc2  "I think a money machine is what is really on his mind," Revrisond was quoted as saying by detik.com news portal in Yogyakarta. \par \par \uc2  Teten Masduki of the Indonesian Corruption Watch said the President's decision is nonsense. It's aimed only at protecting the bad conglomerates. \par \par \uc2  "Taking legal action against criminals will not hamper the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  wheels," Teten said. \par \par \uc2  "This is a bad \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  of the current government," he added. \par \par \uc2  Farid R. Faqih, coordinator of Government Watch (GOWA), shared Teten's view, saying the President's decision was entirely illogical. \par \par \uc2  "Their businesses will still be able to run normally even if legal action is taken against the founding shareholders," Farid said. \par \par \uc2  Moreover, since the three business groups have now been under government control, legal proceedings against the three businessmen would not in anyway stop the businesses' operations, Farid said. (rei/rms/bby) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2000 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010812dwal001pi\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
