\par\par \b \uc2  Hotel owners face changing times with optimism. \b0\par\par\uc2  By Mehru Jaffer \par \uc2 1,624 \uc2 words\par \uc2 22 October 2000\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  13 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2000 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Despite a chain of challenges faced by owners, hotels seem to be here to stay. \par \par \uc2  "We have no major worries," said a confident Fabrice Burtin of Accor Asia/Pacific. \par \par \uc2  Fabrice said business from overseas remains \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  but domestically the middle management market is solid, providing up to 70 percent occupancy. \par \par \uc2  The extreme confidence at Accor is a direct result of having made great inroads into the new mid-market sector, which is predicted as having a far greater potential than expensive hotels, especially in a population-rich country like Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  With an oversupply of first-class and luxury hotels in most Asian cities, the crying need is to provide internationally operated hotels to the fast expanding middle-income group of people as well. \par \par \uc2  Over the past decade, Accor has perhaps been the only one, apart from Holiday Inn, to penetrate premises beyond just primary cities and establish property in secondary cities all over the region. \par \par \uc2  Much competition is expected from ITT Sheraton's Compass, Marriott's Courtyard, Shangri-La's Traders and Inter-Continental's Forum brand, all pushing hard to make their presence felt in the mid-market. \par \par \uc2  Accor Asia/Pacific manages hotels under the brand name of Sofitel, Novotel, Mercure, Ibis and Formula 1, currently operating 75 hotels in Asia. \par \par \uc2  Under an aggressive expansion plan, Accor is expected to add 34 hotels with 6,053 rooms to its 75-property portfolio in the near future and plans to focus primarily on Indonesia, the world's fourth most populous country. \par \par \uc2  The international hotel group has 25 hotels and resorts in Indonesia and its network includes all key destinations, such as Jakarta, Surabaya and Medan. \par \par \uc2  It operates in 3,400 countries around the world, including 170 in the Asia-Pacific region, concentrating also on secondary cities that are expected to gain in importance over a period of time. \par \par \uc2  Accor is pursuing this particular \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  despite the fact that the payoff from the secondary market will not be immediate and profits are expected to flood in only in the long run. \par \par \uc2  However, the future in this sector looks bright for the simple reason that most primary Asian cities are groaning under a load of too much human, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and political activity. \par \par \uc2  It is hoped that sooner rather than later the secondary cities will be allowed to share the burden concentrated today in just certain centers of each country. \par \par \uc2  Secondary cities around the region are almost begging for decent accommodations at more affordable prices for members of the Asian middle class as well as western tourists in search of culturally rich but less crowded dwellings for both business and vacation. \par \par \uc2  At present there is a wide gap between the demand and what is actually available for the average traveler. \par \par \uc2  The boom in the hotel industry is a direct result of Asia Pacific's phenomenal \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  achievements in the past two decades. \par \par \uc2  The tiger economies of Asia created new markets, wealth and the fastest growing middle class, which has supplied the hospitality industry and tourism with unparalleled growth opportunities. \par \par \uc2  Visitor arrivals, tourist receipts and a supply of hotel rooms were highest in 1996. \par \par \uc2  Total arrivals for the region reached 94.3 million in the same year, peaking at almost 7.8 percent over the previous year. \par \par \uc2  Some 2.9 million beds were added between 1980 and 1995 at a compound annual growth rate of 10.9 percent, encouraging international business and leisure travelers to visit Asia, many for the first time. \par \par \uc2  In a special report, Arthur Anderson's Asia/Pacific offices offered an analysis of the Asian hotel industry from a view of the impact of the hotel boom on select Asian cities, the future development plans of major hotel operators in Asia and the challenges facing operators in this increasingly competitive market with a substantial oversupply in first class accommodations in most of the region's primary cities. \par \par \uc2  Tourism in the region galloped to double-digit increases in recent years despite the reduced annual growth rates since 1995. \par \par \uc2  And regional markets here offer dramatically different profiles when it comes to new hotel development. \par \par \uc2  East Asia and the Pacific registered the quickest increase in hotel accommodation measured by beds, adding 2.9 million between 1980 and 1995, representing a compound annual growth rate of 10.9 percent. \par \par \uc2  This is, of course, likely to grow in the 21st century with countries with larger populations, like China, India and Indonesia,showing better opportunities for hotel development. \par \par \uc2  The history of Asian hospitality is long and illustrious. However, formal attempts to provide safe lodging and excellent food day after day at a cost is comparatively modern. \par \par \uc2  The earliest accommodation for travelers followed the English and Dutch examples of inns. \par \par \uc2  During colonial days lodging was available at all seaports. There were bars where sailors could fasten their hammocks on hooks in the backroom and more costly accommodations even offered bunks. \par \par \uc2  Luxurious inns then had rooms with several beds big enough for more than one person to sleep in. \par \par \uc2  The American innkeeper, however, did away with old, European ideas of class, title and background. \par \par \uc2  In America, anybody who could pay for the goods or services received was treated like a king. \par \par \uc2  The capitalist system born out of freedom and the desire to get rich offered the best to anyone who was willing to pay. \par \par \uc2  The first hotel opened in New York in 1794. With 73 rooms it was considered a large property in a city that was home at that time to approximately 30,000 people. \par \par \uc2  Apart from accommodation, the City Hotel offered meeting rooms and eventually became a very popular center of social activity. \par \par \uc2  The first five-star hotel, by the standards of 1829, was the Tremont House in Boston with 170 rooms. \par \par \uc2  Part of the luxury were water pitchers in each room as well as a bowl for washing up. \par \par \uc2  Free soap was included in the price. What was started long ago is still being perfected and updated to accommodate the modern day guest. \par \par \uc2  To prepare itself for the future, Accor recently introduced its Blue Phone services. The Blue Phone, available in all of its hotel lobbies, is free of charge and is expected to provide the local and international traveler with fast and efficient access to reservations. \par \par \uc2  "Accor operates the most comprehensive global hotel network. With properties ranging from five star through to \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , we offer our guests a vast range of hotel choices in 140 countries," explained Oswald Pichler, director of operations for Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  Occupancies increased annually in Jakarta between 1993 and 1996, however, competition due to new supply limited increases in room rates, keeping room yields relatively stable. \par \par \uc2  By the end of 1997, the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis and the devaluation of the currency caused domestic and social unrest and political riots in Jakarta and other parts of Indonesia, severely affecting both national and international demand for accommodation here. \par \par \uc2  Hotel values dropped after having peaked in 1996. \par \par \uc2  As supply has remained relatively stable during the last four years, hotels in Bali have benefited from rising occupancy levels and average room rates. \par \par \uc2  The combination of new supply and a growing negative perception of Indonesia by travelers resulted in a drop in room yields during the first part of 1998. \par \par \uc2  After the resignation of former president Soeharto in early 1998, the country is concentrating on rescuing its national banking system and \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Among other plans the government has introduced are new borrowers, allowing transactions to take place more easily. \par \par \uc2  Although the immediate \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  outlook for Indonesia is improving in line with the implementation of new laws and the strengthening of the rupiah, hoteliers are also faced with new challenges as markets continue to experience severe financial problems. \par \par \uc2  This is likely to interrupt domestic developments for the time being until financial institutions have identified a new way forward. \par \par \uc2  There is also a shortage of skilled labor in almost all Asian markets, especially as new hotels come on line. \par \par \uc2  Hotels have to be aware of any rise in costs as profit margins will inevitably slide if hotels do not reinvent their primary processes and eliminate services not sought by today's traveler. \par \par \uc2  The high staff to room ratio of the past may well decline during the next five years to levels much closer to what is common in Europe and the United States. \par \par \uc2  To continuously adjust business according to circumstances without compromising the dignity of the flag that flies on the rooftop is the greatest challenge before Peter Carmichael, the general manager at Jakarta's Shangri-La hotel. But he is optimistic. \par \par \uc2  "My optimism springs out of the very challenge that we face. Every day we experience difficulties, adjust, regroup and carry on in the hope of better times to come," Carmichael told The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2  Carmichael is convinced that better times will definitely come, but when is the big question. \par \par \uc2  The Shangri-La, a major player in Asia, had enjoyed an occupancy rate of 70 percent in precrisis times, before it dipped to 48 percent. \par \par \uc2  The company continues to rapidly expand its portfolio of deluxe city hotels and resorts. Presently, it operates 35 properties with a total of 17,000 rooms and has plans to add 11 hotels with a total of 5,718 rooms in Asia, mainly in primary and secondary cities of China. \par \par \uc2  Hotel owners and operators will need to embrace many changes, improve processes and introduce advanced technology to realize a future they are looking for. \par \par \uc2  They will have to diversify and innovate to the satisfaction of not just those with money but also the ballooning middle class so eager to use its increasingly disposable income for leisure, and for making more money. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2000 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010812dwam001kb\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  Finance Minister - private capital outflow on the rise. \b0\par\par\uc2 562 \uc2 words\par \uc2 24 October 2000\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2000 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  Private capital net outflow is expected to reach \par \par \uc2  US$11,162 billion this year, as the government has targeted the rupiah at \par \par \uc2  7.300 per US dollar. \par \par \uc2  Finance Minister Prijadi Praptosuhardjo said in 1998 and 1999 private \par \par \uc2  capital outflow stood at respectively US$13,846 billion and US$9,923 \par \par \uc2  billion. \par \par \uc2  In 2000, he added, the figure is expected to reach US$ 11,162 billion. \par \par \uc2  "It's quite a source of concern," he told House members here yesterday. \par \par \uc2  Reasons for the huge capital outflow, said Prijadi, are the maturity dates \par \par \uc2  of private sector loans and the late entry of fresh funds into Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  Capital outflow, especially in the form of portfolio investments, he said, \par \par \uc2  has an impact on the rupiah's exchange rate and is very sensitive to all \par \par \uc2  sorts of information. \par \par \uc2  "Events that upset political stability and security in this country have \par \par \uc2  put pressure on the rupiah." \par \par \uc2  He added that foreign direct investment (FDI) in 1996 stood at US$6,2 \par \par \uc2  billion but that according to UNCTAD in 1998 and 1999 the figure declined \par \par \uc2  sharply as a result of a crisis in confidence. \par \par \uc2  "In the past two years the net FDI was a negative US$356 million and \par \par \uc2  US$3,3 billion." \par \par \uc2  On the other hand, global FDI through mergers and acquisitions of \par \par \uc2  transnational companies stood at US$865 billion last year, and is expected \par \par \uc2  to break through the US$1 trillion mark this year. \par \par \uc2  Prijadi further said since September 2000 the rupiah fell by 40%. \par \par \uc2  A finance ministry yesterday said he is convinced that the rupiah would \par \par \uc2  reach 7.300/US$ next year. \par \par \uc2  "There is going to be a surprise," he said. \par \par \uc2  The finance minister said he that a 7.300 per US$ rate in the new \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\par \par \uc2  is optimistically realistic. \par \par \uc2  Several factors that play a role in the exchange rate of the rupiah, he \par \par \uc2  said, are whether the current rate is under-valued, over-valued or \par \par \uc2  fair-valued and how the current account now performs and its prospects in \par \par \uc2  2001. \par \par \uc2  Also, forex \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2 , capital, political stability and its prospects next \par \par \uc2  year. \par \par \uc2  Prijadi said that \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  says that 8.625/US$ in September 2000 \par \par \uc2  [now 8.850] shows that the rupiah is undervalued. \par \par \uc2  "The government insists on 7.300/US$ despite the fact that the rupiah is \par \par \uc2  now still weak." \par \par \uc2  Previously, he added, the government and the House had agreed on 7 \par \par \uc2  September 2000 to peg the rupiah at 6.800 to 7.800 against the dollar, but \par \par \uc2  later revised it to 7.300. \par \par \uc2  The current account has been encouraging for the past three years, he said. \par \par \uc2  "In 1998 and 1999 the current account saw a surplus of respectively \par \par \uc2  US44,097 billion and US$5,783 billion." \par \par \uc2  In 2000 the surplus is expected to rise to US$7,627 billion, he said. \par \par \uc2  Forex \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  in 1999 stood at US$27,054 billion and that in 2000 the \par \par \uc2  figure would rise to US$27,243 billion. \par \par \uc2  "In 2001 the current account and forex \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  are expected to show signs \par \par \uc2  of encouragement," he added. \par \par \uc2  Prijadi sees a better macro \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in 2001 compared to that of 2000, \par \par \uc2  despite \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the socio-political situation of the country. \par \par \uc2  He added that several macro indicators in the first semester of 2000 have \par \par \uc2  been positive to the extent they show early signs of recovery. (dj/ens). \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis0020010804dwao000p5\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  President's ability to convince market in doubt. \b0\par\par\uc2 491 \uc2 words\par \uc2 26 October 2000\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2