e growth rate does not reflect her true potential, which is 5%-8%. \par \par \uc2  The banking situation would also remain problematical for some time to come as many government macro policies are inconsistent, preventing many from making sound business plans, said banker Thomas Suyatno in a seminar on \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recover and laws here Tuesday. \par \par \uc2  Thomas noted that on one side banks are forced to buy funds at a steep cost - SBI \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  keep going up, forcing banks to raise their \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  - on the other side banks refuse to release funds in fear of 'bleeding' and a drop in its capital adequate ratio (CAR). \par \par \uc2  Economist Faisal Basri said many policies shackle banks, causing banks not only to become unhealthy but also to remain so. \par \par \uc2  "Many sound companies need funds and get them from foreign, not national, banks. This is strange, there is something wrong," Faisal said. \par \par \uc2  Thomas said that so long as there are no fresh funds, any credits channeled would make banks' CAR fall. \par \par \uc2  He does not rule out banks soon becoming 'patients' of IBRA. \par \par \uc2  Bank Internasional Indonesia director Rudy N. Hamdani also predicted that many banks would no longer be able to sustain their operations next year. \par \par \uc2  "Unless banks merge or invite outside investors, they would not be able to survive and would close down," he said here Tuesday. \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis0020010804dwaq000pl\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  'Decoupling of  \highlight22\uc2 economic \highlight\uc2  and political activities start to take shape'. \b0\par\par\uc2 388 \uc2 words\par \uc2 26 October 2000\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2000 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  The decoupling of political and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activities are starting to take place in which the government's policies no longer have impacts on the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  indicator recovery. \par \par \uc2  According to Indef Director Faisal Basri, the government's \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  absence no longer affects the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  indicators. \par \par \uc2  "When the 10 program was launched, the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  indicator went worst. While during the CGI it had no affects. The conservative state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  draft also had not affect," Faisal told a seminar on \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery and law enforcement in the reform era on Tuesday. \par \par \uc2  According to Faisal, this shows the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  is fatigue in facing the political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and that the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  started to roll by itself. \par \par \uc2  In order to improve the government, President KH Abdurrahman Wahid needs to adopt collective leadership or share power in order to prevent bleeding like in the banking sector, which eventually had to be liquidated, in this case the president has to be impeached. \par \par \uc2  Faisal described Wahid's government like a bank with low capital adequacy ratio (CAR) that needs to be recapitalized, but the capital is not injected in terms of fresh funds and therefore it continues to bleed. \par \par \uc2  "If it is recapped but is still bleeding, well like what BI used to say, let 's liquidate it. I analog the liquidation as an impeachment and if he doesn' t want to be impeached he has to prevent it from bleeding," said Faisal. \par \par \uc2  "In the banking sector we describe Gus Dur as bleeding heavily because since the very beginning, Gus Dur did not have enough to become a President, like a bank that failed to meet the 4% capital a