\par\par \b \uc2  In search of a person who can lead. \b0\par\par\uc2 968 \uc2 words\par \uc2 30 October 2000\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  4 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2000 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  This is the first of two articles on leadership by Dr. Ignas Kleden, a sociologist and executive director of The Go-East Institute (Institute for East-Indonesian Affairs), Jakarta. \par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): A leader in a stable society can work from behind. His leadership is successful if things are running well and people are not necessarily aware of his presence and interference. The existing norms and values are sufficient guidelines to orientate his followers as to how to behave. \par \par \uc2  By contrast in a crisis situation, a leader becomes a necessity. He must show his presence, appearing in front of his people to restore the confidence among his followers and to assure them that though they are deeply embedded in disorientation, everything will be alright again because they can put everything under control. \par \par \uc2  A leader becomes the personification of norms and values which in a time of crisis are very liable to become shaky and indefinite. The loosening of values and norms would not lead to increasing confusion if people still have somebody to look up to, somebody who represents in his personality and behavior - steadiness, firmness in conviction, sovereignty over problems and pressures, and moral courage to face up to even the worst possible situation. To put it philosophically, a leader is by definition a man for others and never a man for himself. \par \par \uc2  This is clear in theoretical terms but becomes blurred in real practice. A leader might be undaunted in the face of troubles and even threats and yet this could become sheer obstinacy if what he tries to defend is not for the benefit of his followers but for his own self-interest. \par \par \uc2  In the same vein, a man can remain cool and stable in the midst of pressing problems and \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 , yet this could be far away from real composure and firmness and instead be mere indifference if he has no empathy with the concern of the many who are suffering. \par \par \uc2  A leader seems to be a man (or a woman for that matter) who not only can think for the people but also can feel with them. \par \par \uc2  Sometimes it is difficult to understand whether a leader is really doing his best to render his people to be seriously aware of their troubles; or perhaps he is trying to explain away the troubles by making fun of them or even just ridiculing looming issues that are burdensome and troublesome. \par \par \uc2  There is usually only a hair's breadth difference between bringing people to optimism and hope and leading them to quasi-ignorance or illusion. Needless to say, there are problems which by nature can never be glossed over by means of trivializing their urgency. \par \par \uc2  Whatever politicians would say about the rising unemployment and the reduction of \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  for fuel, people can never be made forgetful, let alone ignorant, of the additional \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  burden they might not be able to shoulder. \par \par \uc2  Also, we cannot simply say "don't worry" or "why bother" to those who have lost two or three members of their family in the killings and violent conflicts in Ambon, Papua, and Aceh. At the same time more than 100 East Timorese who chose to join the Republic during the last referendum in East Timor are still waiting desperately for resettlement. \par \par \uc2  From a national point of view, it is somewhat embarrassing that the issue of humanitarianism has become actual and important just after the killing of three United Nations workers. \par \par \uc2  Likewise, the situation of political refugees and the solution to the problem of prointegration militias were given more attention after the United States threatened to lay an \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  embargo on Indonesia if the militias were not disarmed entirely. \par \par \uc2  There is no denying the fact that killing in whatever form is a terrible thing. But what has been said so far about the death of political refugees both because of miserable protection and poor accommodation as well as violent treatment? Was any mention ever made of this loss of lives as a humanitarian problem? Double standards in moral judgment and political stance are still the order of the day in Atambua or in other parts of the globe. \par \par \uc2  Indonesia has no doubt been heavily hit by a multifaceted crisis. The demand for \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery, for example, is still aggravated by the requirement of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform. Recovery in \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activities should necessarily be accompanied by a reform in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  structure. \par \par \uc2  The government and people are unfortunately faced with this double task. Reform without recovery is very likely to lead to a total paralysis of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , whereas recovery without reform would bring the national \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  back to square one, with all the requisites for another crisis. \par \par \uc2  This condition is made worse by the political crisis originating in at least two sorts of development. Political openness has provided the opportunity for much more exercise of political freedom and democratic rights without much consideration of their costs and benefits. \par \par \uc2  Continuous demonstrations and protests for whatever reasons have brought about political hullabaloos which exceed the available political carrying capacity. Meanwhile regions which were neglected and whose populations fell victim to political violence during the New Order, are now standing up to demand the return of their \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and political rights, amounting to unexpected regional insurrections. \par \par \uc2  Past \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  losses and political harassments should be taken into account by the present government in order to come to terms with regional disappointments satisfactorily. \par \par \uc2  In Aceh such disappointment takes the form of regional revolt, in Papua a separatist movement, whereas in Ambon it is manipulated by external forces to become a quasi inter-religious conflict. If we keep lingering at the face value of these insurrections, we would easily come to misleading analytical conclusions and consequently to wrong political decisions. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2000 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010812dwau002h5\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  Rizal to sue distruntled politicians over rupiah depreciation. \b0\par\par\uc2 306 \uc2 words\par \uc2 1 November 2000\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2000 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  Coordinating Minister for the \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Rizal Ramly \par \par \uc2  said he would make disgrunted politicians pay the cost of rupiah \par \par \uc2  depreciation because their manoeuvers to remove President Gus Dur from \par \par \uc2  power had created a great deal of market \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The minister said \par \par \uc2  the cost reached US$10 million during last week alone. \par \par \uc2  "This is equal to Rp 80 billion and I will make these politicians pay the \par \par \uc2  damage," he said. \par \par \uc2  He said the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  was actually getting better but was suddenly jolted so \par \par \uc2  severely because of the manoeuvers of such politicians to oust the \par \par \uc2  President. \par \par \uc2  This was 